According to the columns' name of the 3 yellow Taxi's data, it is clear that no new features is added to make the different. Where the each columns is present for:

Feature Description
VendorID A code indicating the TPEP provider that provided the record.

1= Creative Mobile Technologies, LLC; 2= VeriFone Inc
tpep_pickup_datetime The date and time when the meter was engaged.
tpep_dropoff_datetime The date and time when the meter was disengaged.
passenger_count The number of passengers in the vehicle.
This is a driver-entered value.
trip_distance The elapsed trip distance in miles reported by the taximeter.
RatecodeID The final rate code in effect at the end of the trip.

1= Standard rate
2= JFK
3= Newark
4= Nassau or Westchester
5= Negotiated fare
6= Group ride
store_and_fwd_flag This flag indicates whether the trip record was held in vehicle memory before sending to the vendor,
aka “store and forward,” because the vehicle did not have a connection to the server.

Y= store and forward trip.
N= not a store and forward trip.
PULocationID TLC Taxi Zone in which the taximeter was engaged
DOLocationID TLC Taxi Zone in which the taximeter was disengaged
payment_type A numeric code signifying how the passenger paid for the trip.

0= Credit card
1= Cash
2= No charge
3= Dispute
4= Unknown
5=Voided trip
fare_amount The time-and-distance fare calculated by the meter.
extra Miscellaneous extras and surcharges. Currently, this only includes
the \$0.50 and \$1 rush hour and overnight charges.
mta_tax \$0.50 MTA tax that is automatically triggered based on the metered rate in use.
tip_amount This field is automatically populated for credit card tips. Cash tips are not included.
tolls_amount Total amount of all tolls paid in trip.
improvement_surcharge \$0.30 improvement surcharge assessed trips at the flag drop. The improvement surcharge began being levied in 2015.
total_amount The total amount charged to passengers. Does not include cash tips.
congestion_surcharge Total amount collected in trip for NYS congestion surcharge.
Airport_fee \$1.25 for pick up only at LaGuardia and John F. Kennedy Airports

Merge data and analyze the trend through 3 months

In [ ]:
# Add new columns month to make it specific, because the data will be merege later
data1['month'] = 'January'
data3['month'] = 'March'
data6['month'] = 'June'
# Change the airport_fee to Airport_fee to make it the same as March and June data
data1.rename(columns={"airport_fee": "Airport_fee"}, inplace=True)
# Merge 3 data to 1 to analyze
data_merge = pd.concat([data1, data3, data6], ignore_index=True)
In [ ]:
Vendor_month = data_merge.groupby(['VendorID', 'month']).size().unstack(fill_value=0)  # Group VendorID and month
Vendor_month_percent = Vendor_month.div(Vendor_month.sum(axis=0), axis=1) * 100  # Get the percentage of VendorID per month

# Plot the bar plot
ax = Vendor_month_percent.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(10, 8))
plt.title('Vendor ID of 3 different months')
plt.xlabel('VendorID')
plt.ylabel('Percentage')

# Add number of percentage
for p in ax.patches:
    ax.annotate(f'{p.get_height():.2f}%', (p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2., p.get_height()), ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=9)
plt.show()

According to this plot, the percentage of VendorID is not much different through 3 months. There are only one specific value which is the VendorID equal to 6 is only appears in March and June. However, this value is not much, compare to the value 1 and 2 of VendorID

Conclusion:

According to some category variable plots, including VendorID, RatecodeID, Payment Type, and Number of passenger as percentage, they show the clear similarity through all 3 months and not much differences have been recorded. However, in VendorID there is new ID, which is equal to 6 have been found in March and June.

Based on some amount plots, the slightly increase trend have been found in income from January to June. This trend appears through all kind of amount.

In conclusion, the trends of VendorID, RatecodeID, Payment Type, and Number of passenger is not have the significant differences through 3 months, but the amount income is increase from January to June

According to the set values of each feature including VendorID, passenger_count, trip_distance, RatecodeID, store_and_fwd_flag, PULocationID, DOLocationID, payment_type; there are 3 values that are uncommon including passenger_count equal to 0, trip_distance = 0, and RatecodeID with value 99.

The reason why these 3 columns are uncommon are the trip cannot be 0 miles, the trip of taxi cannot be hold if there is no passenger and the RatecodeID with value 99 which is not include in the category.

Moreover, when the total amount of the trips, which have no passenger or 0 miles distances, the sum of total amount way more than 0. However, the number of passenger on a trip can only be entered by taxi drivers, this can be the mistake of them.

As a result, these 2 columns RatecodeID, trip_distance should be the 2 columns that contain the noisy values.

# prompt: fix svm model to predict total_amount of data by other feature

from sklearn import svm
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Split the data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(data.drop('total_amount', axis=1), data['total_amount'], test_size=0.25)

# Scale the data
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test = scaler.transform(X_test)

# Create the SVM model
model = svm.SVR()

# Hyperparameter tuning
parameters = {'C': [0.1, 1, 10, 100, 1000], 'gamma': [0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 1, 10]}
grid_search = GridSearchCV(model, parameters, cv=5)
grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the test set
y_pred = grid_search.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
print('Mean squared error:', mse)

# Save the model

Task 5: Conclusion¶

1. Summarize the key findings from your data analysis

  • By loading 3 months of the data and analyzed the difference between them, the trend of yellow taxi through these 3 months is seem not thing changes except the income from all kind of money amount, which have a significant increase from January to June.

  • The data have outliers, these outliers can effect the result on the correlation to analyzed more about them, so they are removed to get the better correlation (Only for the correlation matrix).

  • The data have some missing values, which only account for 2.39% of total data in January, so they are removed.

  • The longer the trip distance, the more income in fare and total amount have been recorded.

  • The data in January shows that the trip distance in weekends is longer than weekdays, as well as the number of passengers per trip. The number of TPEP provider as VeriFone Inc is mostly 3 time higher than Creative Mobile Technologies, LLC.

  • Most of the trip is usually run at 6pm, the most active time is from 2pm to 7pm.

  • The fare_amount shows the high correlation with tip amount and not have correlation with number of passenger.
